<div id="review_1026088689" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1026088689" />
    <a title="Conor" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30552336-conor"><img alt="Conor" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400278909p2/30552336.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1026088689?book_show_action=true">Aug 13, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Conor" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Conor" href="/user/show/30552336-conor">Conor</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30552336-conor?shelf=awesome-books-are-awesome">awesome-books-are-awesome</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1026088689" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12063651268857434162">When I was about 11 or 12 most of the lads in my class were really big into professional wrestling. This mostly consisted of dropping piledrivers, powerbombs and inverted neckbreakers on each other. When I wasn&apos;t opening up a can of whoop-ass on my frineds I also watched the shows, read a couple of autobiographies and even learned the terminology. Example: &apos;The face beat the heel in order to get over&apos;. If you don&apos;t understand that, you&apos;re a &apos;mark&apos;. Sorry. (Incidentally there&apos;s a pretty big overl</span>
  <span id="freeText12063651268857434162" style="display:none">When I was about 11 or 12 most of the lads in my class were really big into professional wrestling. This mostly consisted of dropping piledrivers, powerbombs and inverted neckbreakers on each other. When I wasn't opening up a can of whoop-ass on my frineds I also watched the shows, read a couple of autobiographies and even learned the terminology. Example: 'The face beat the heel in order to get over'. If you don't understand that, you're a 'mark'. Sorry. (Incidentally there's a pretty big overlap between wrestling and carnie terminology). Although It's been around 5 years since I read this book or followed wrestling seriously I still remember this one as the stand-out in the genre (do the ghost-written life-stories of guys who pretend to fight in their underwear count as a literary genre?). But I digress; Foley's warm, humorous accounts of his life make this both the definitive book of it's kind and also more than 'just' a wrestling book. <br /><br />Whereas other wrestling books tend to follow a predictable formula and to have a similar tone this one was unique. Unlike all of the other 'autobiographies', this one was actually written by the man himself. Wrestlers' autobiographies (even to my 12 year old sense of literary worth) often seemed like lazy, cynical attempts to make money and settle scores with people the writer had a grudge against (the entire 'genre' often reminded me of the Christmas special episode of father Ted where Ted makes a speech in which all of the people he wants to mention are grouped into the categories 'liars' and 'wankers'. A classic ep.). However in this book Foley demonstrates a genuine love of writing. While that love of writing has resulted in this book being somewhat overly drawn out (about 2 to 3 times the length of most wrestling books) it also resulted in a level of candour, intelligence and good-humour completely unmatched by any other books in the genre.<br /><br />Overall this is both the definitive wrestling book and a good book read on it's own merits. While wrestling fans will likely appreciate more of the references and insights this is the only book of it's type that I would also recommend to someone who has no interest in or knowledge of pro wrestling.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12063651268857434162" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


